revision.text:
{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = A History of Chinese Literature | image = <!-- include the file, px and alt: [[File:Example.jpg|200px|Cover]] --> | caption = | author = [[Herbert Giles]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = British | language = English | series = | subject = History | genre = | publisher = | pub_date = 1901 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 448 | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''A History of Chinese Literature''''' is a history of [[Chinese literature]] written by [[Herbert Giles]], and published in 1901.
Although there had been surveys of Chinese literature in Japanese, it was the first such survey to appear in English.{{sfnb|Wang|2013| p = 9}} In his preface, Giles claims that such a work of history was not already available, even in Chinese, <ref>{{cite journal | author = J. Dyer Ball | journal = [[The China Review]] | title = Dr. Giles's History of Chinese Literature | pages = 207–210 | volume = 25 | issue = 4 | year = 1901 | url = http://sunzi1.lib.hku.hk/hkjo/view/26/2600451.pdf }}</ref> since Chinese scholars realized the "uttter hopelessness" of "achieving even comparative success in a general historical survey of the subject". But he adds that "It may be said without offence that a work which would be inadequate to the requirements of a native public, may properly be submitted to English readers as an introduction into the great field which lies beyond". A large part of the book is devoted to translations, "enabling the Chinese author, so far as is possible, to speak for himself".{{sfnb|Giles|1901|p = v-vi}}
==Reception and influence== The scholar and writer [[Lin Yutang]] commented that "'History of Chinese Literature' was a misnomer; it was a series of attempted essays on certain Chinese works, and was not even an outline covering the successive periods.” <ref>quoted in {{Cite| first =|last = Wang |title = The ''Alter Ego'' Perspectives of Literary Historiography |year = 2013 | ref = none| p = 9}}</ref>
[[Qian Zhongshu]] noted what he called an "amusing mistake" in Giles' "very readable book." Giles ::Giles gives a complete version of [[Sikong Du|Ssu-k'ung Tu]]'s 'philosophical poem, consisting of twenty-four apparently unconnected stanzas'. This poem, according to Professor Giles, 'is admirably adapted to exhibit the forms under which pure Taoism commends itself to the mind of a cultivated scholar.' This is what Professor Giles thinks Ssu-K'ung Tu to have done, but what Ssu-K'ung Tu really does is to convey in imageries of surpassing beauty the impressions made upon a sensitive mind by twenty-four different kinds of poetry—'pure, ornate, grotesque', etc. <ref>"[http://www.chinaheritagequarterly.org/features.php?searchterm=030_literature.inc&issue=030 On 'Old Chinese Poetry]," The China Critic, VI:50 (14 December 1933): 1206-1208., reprinted at The China Heritage Quarterly 39.31 June September 2012</ref>
[[Ezra Pound#''Ripostes'' and translations|Ezra Pound]] used Giles' translations as the basis for what have been called his English "translations of translations".{{sfnb|Kern|1996| p = [https://books.google.com/?id=uWeRGJW5sNwC&pg=PA185 173]}}
==Editions== {{Wikisource|A History of Chinese Literature}} * {{cite|first = Herbert A.| last = Giles|title =A History of Chinese Literature| year = 1901| publisher = Appleton| place = New York and London|ref = harv}} Available online at: [https://books.google.com/books?id=EyFMAAAAMAAJ Google Books]; [https://archive.org/details/historyofchinese00gileiala A History of Chinese Literature] [[Internet Archive]]; [http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/43711 A History of Chinese Literature] [[Project Gutenberg]].
