'''Taco Trucks At Every Mosque''' (also '''#TacoTrucksAtEveryMosque''') is a community initiative started in [[Orange County, California]] that aims to bring together [[Muslim]] and [[Latino]] communities through sharing food. The events were the idea of Rida Hamida and Ben Vazquez. The first event took place on June 3, 2017 and have taken place throughout California, in [[Mexico]] and [[Milwaukee]].
== History == While [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latinos]] currently make up around a third of [[Orange County, California|Orange County's]] residents and there are 120,000 [[Muslim|Muslims]], both minority groups do not have much political power.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2018/02/08/584057034/building-a-latino-muslim-coalition-with-tacotrucksateverymosque|title=Building A Latino-Muslim Coalition With #TacoTrucksAtEveryMosque|last=Arellano|first=Gustavo|date=8 February 2018|publisher=NPR.org|access-date=2018-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208194746/https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2018/02/08/584057034/building-a-latino-muslim-coalition-with-tacotrucksateverymosque|archive-date=8 February 2018|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> In 2016, both groups of people saw an increase in documented [[Hate crime|hate crimes]] against their communities.<ref name=":0" /> Also in 2016, [[Marco Gutierrez]] of the ''Latinos for Trump'' group, said, "You're going to have [[taco trucks on every corner]]."<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/12/23/most-influential-2017-rida-hamida-and-benjamin-vazquez/|title=Most Influential 2017: Rida Hamida and Benjamin Vazquez bring halal tacos, cultural mingling, to mosques throughout Southern California.|last=Bharath|first=Deepa|date=2017-12-23|work=Orange County Register|access-date=2018-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223184600/https://www.ocregister.com/2017/12/23/most-influential-2017-rida-hamida-and-benjamin-vazquez/|archive-date=23 December 2017|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> When [[Donald Trump]] won the presidency, there was an increase in the amount of both anti-immigrant and anti-Muslim feelings in American culture.<ref name=":1" /> After Trump won, Rida Hamida, a Muslim from [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]], and Benjamin Vazquez, who is a Latino from [[Santa Ana, California|Santa Ana]], met and began a discussion about what Muslims and Latinos could learn from one another.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-tacos-ramadan-20170604-story.html|title=Muslim and Latino groups unite during Ramadan, breaking fast with tacos at mosques|last=Do|first=Anh|date=4 June 2017|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref> Hamida and Vasquez thought about the [[Food truck|taco truck]] idea and about bringing Muslims to [[Mexican cuisine|Mexican restaurants]]. In the end, they decided to bring taco trucks to [[Mosque|mosques]].<ref name=":1" /> Using the taco trucks (or ''loncheras'') was also a way to empower Latinos.<ref name=":0" /> Taco Trucks At Every Mosque is also a way for the two minority communities to get to know one another and combat the fear of immigrant communities.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2017-06-08/muslim-and-latino-communities-southern-california-mix-during-ramadan-thanks-taco|title=Muslim and Latino communities in Southern California mix during Ramadan — thanks to taco trucks|last=Leville|first=David|date=8 June 2017|publisher=Public Radio International|access-date=2018-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722090147/https://www.pri.org/stories/2017-06-08/muslim-and-latino-communities-southern-california-mix-during-ramadan-thanks-taco|archive-date=22 July 2017|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref>
The first event, an [[iftar]], took place on June 3, 2017 at the [[Islamic Center of Santa Ana]] and was attended by 600 people.<ref name=":1" /> The [[halal]] tacos were given free to people attending the iftar.<ref name=":0" /> The second event, a few weeks later at the [[Islamic Center of Orange County|Islamic Society of Orange County]], was attended by 1,400 people.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tpr.org/post/taco-trucks-every-mosque-brings-latinos-and-muslims-together-during-ramadan|title='Taco Trucks At Every Mosque' Brings Latinos And Muslims Together During Ramadan|last=|first=|date=21 June 2017|publisher=Texas Public Radio|access-date=2018-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701211543/http://tpr.org/post/taco-trucks-every-mosque-brings-latinos-and-muslims-together-during-ramadan|archive-date=1 July 2017|dead-url=yes|language=en|df=}}</ref> The groups raise money to pay for the tacos and in 2017, visited every mosque in Orange County during [[Ramadan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://aldianews.com/articles/politics/immigration/tacotrucksateverymosque-bringing-latinos-and-muslims-together/48487|title=#TacoTrucksAtEveryMosque: Bringing Latinos and Muslims together.|last=Rodes|first=Andrea|date=2017-06-05|work=AL DÍA News|access-date=2018-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610044230/http://aldianews.com/articles/politics/immigration/tacotrucksateverymosque-bringing-latinos-and-muslims-together/48487|archive-date=10 June 2017|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> Because Ramadan is also a time of charity, the taco truck plan was a good fit.<ref name=":2" /> Even though the events focus on the Latino and Muslim communities, everyone is welcome.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/taco-trucks-at-every-mosque-celebrated-latino-and-muslim-unity-in-garden-grove-last-night-8187697/|title='Taco Trucks at Every Mosque' Celebrated Latino and Muslim Unity in Garden Grove Last Night|last=|first=|date=15 June 2017|website=OC Weekly|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216004339/https://www.ocweekly.com/taco-trucks-at-every-mosque-celebrated-latino-and-muslim-unity-in-garden-grove-last-night-8187697/|archive-date=16 February 2018|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref> One person attending the second event hoped that Taco Trucks At Every Mosque would inspire more Muslims to come to Latino events.<ref name=":3" /> Hamida and Vazquez promoted the events on Twitter with the hashtag, #TacoTrucksAtEveryMosque.<ref name=":4" />
== Legacy == The Taco Trucks At Every Mosque events have taken place in communities from [[Baja California]] in [[Mexico]] to [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fox40.com/2018/01/19/fighting-hate-one-halal-taco-at-a-time-local-muslims-and-latinos-join-together-to-promote-unity/|title=‘Fighting Hate One Halal Taco at a Time:’ Local Muslims and Latinos Join Together to Promote Unity|last=Zendehnam|first=Sara|date=2018-01-20|publisher=FOX 40|access-date=2018-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216004717/http://fox40.com/2018/01/19/fighting-hate-one-halal-taco-at-a-time-local-muslims-and-latinos-join-together-to-promote-unity/|archive-date=16 February 2018|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> They have also taken place during [[Eid al-Adha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocweekly.com/taco-trucks-at-every-mosque-goes-to-rosarito-8406717/|title=“Taco Trucks At Every Mosque” Goes to Rosarito for Cross-Border Latino-Muslim Unity…and Tacos!|last=|first=|date=|website=OC Weekly|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216005136/https://www.ocweekly.com/taco-trucks-at-every-mosque-goes-to-rosarito-8406717/|archive-date=16 February 2018|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref> The events have inspired a mosque in [[Milwaukee]], the [[Islamic Society of Milwaukee]], to copy the idea.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/local/milwaukee/2017/06/16/feliz-ramadan-brought-communities-together-food-and-conversations/402151001/|title=Taco Trucks at Every Mosque campaign unites Latinos and Muslims in Milwaukee|last=Noennig|first=Jordyn|date=16 June 2017|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|access-date=2018-02-17|language=en}}</ref> [[Marco Gutierrez]] even posted a video on his [[Instagram]], saying "I tried to warn you people. #TacoTrucksOnEveryCorning {{sic}} has mutated into #TacoTrucksatEveryMosque!"<ref name=":0" />
== See also == * [[Taco trucks on every corner]]
